## Migration Analysis

Your code has **three** patterns that need migration:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---------|----------|-------------|
| **Cancellable work loop** | `while (true)` in `RunLoop` | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| **Blocking call interruption** | `Thread.Interrupt()` to wake `WaitOne` | `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with `token.WaitHandle` |
| **Forced termination** | `Thread.Abort()` fallback | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` — cooperative only |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new ManualResetEvent(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new Queue<string>();
    private readonly object _lock = new object();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var handles = new WaitHandle[] { _newEvent, _cts.Token.WaitHandle };

        while (!_cts.Token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // WaitAny returns index of the signaled handle.
            // Index 0 = new event, Index 1 = cancellation requested.
            int signaled = WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);

            if (signaled == 1) // cancellation token
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            string? item = null;
            lock (_lock)
            {
                if (_queue.Count > 0)
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
            }

            if (item is not null)
                Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();           // signals the token → wakes WaitAny
        _thread?.Join(5000);     // wait for graceful exit
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()`** — cooperative; the loop checks the token.
2. **`Thread.Interrupt()` → removed** — no longer needed; `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with `_cts.Token.WaitHandle` wakes the blocked thread immediately on cancellation.
3. **`while (true)` → `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)`** — the loop voluntarily exits.
4. **Added `IDisposable`** — `CancellationTokenSource` leaks timers/callbacks if not disposed.

## Pitfalls to Watch

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **`WaitOne` doesn't check tokens** | Your original `_newEvent.WaitOne()` will block forever after cancellation. You *must* switch to `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with both handles. |
| **Race between `Set` and `Reset`** | Multiple rapid `Enqueue` calls can signal `_newEvent` while the loop is between `WaitAny` and `Reset`, losing items. Guard `Dequeue` with a count check (shown above). Consider draining the queue in a loop. |
| **No forced kill exists** | If `Handle(item)` hangs, `Cancel()` won't interrupt it — cooperative cancellation only works at checkpoints. Pass the token into `Handle` if it does long-running work. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Causes timer/callback leaks. Always wrap in `using` or implement `IDisposable`. |
| **`Thread.Interrupt` is also obsolete** | `SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9. Don't replace `Abort` with `Interrupt` — both are gone. |
